    <title>Combined summary - HTLC Endorsement for Jamming Mitigation</title>
    <updated>2023-07-02T03:00:33.501575+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/lightning-dev/2023-June/003984.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email thread and subsequent discussions on the Lightning-dev mailing list revolve around the topic of channel jamming in the Lightning Network and the proposed reputation scheme as a mitigation strategy. The reputation scheme involves tracking local reputation for each node's direct peers based on their history with HTLCs forwarded to them. This scheme aims to deter channel jamming attacks by creating a two-part system that includes HTLC endorsement and reputation tracking.One contributor, Antoine, raises concerns about the proposed HTLC endorsement scheme and suggests his own proposal called Staking Credentials as an alternative approach. Antoine emphasizes the need for reputational transitivity between incoming and outgoing traffic and provides a link for further information on Staking Credentials.Carla provides updates on the progress of channel jamming mitigation efforts, including plans to gather data on the use of HTLC endorsement and local reputation tracking. The team intends to experiment with different algorithms for tracking local reputation and observe the effects of endorsement in a logging-only implementation. Carla invites further discussion during an upcoming call.The conversation also discusses the lack of transitivity in reputation acquisition cost between hops in a payment path and its implications for the endorsement scheme. There is uncertainty about the exact implications of dynamic reputation windows on payment reliability. The differentiation between fees charged by a node and reputation revenue is also mentioned.In addition to the main discussion on channel jamming, there are side conversations about writing extensions and deploying them to nodes using implementations like CLN (C-Lightning) and lnmetrics. The possibility of creating an experimental data gathering mechanism for the Lightning Network is discussed, with lnmetrics being suggested as a platform for this purpose.Overall, the email and subsequent discussions highlight the ongoing efforts within the Lightning Network community to address the issue of channel jamming through reputation-based schemes such as HTLC endorsement. The conversations demonstrate collaboration and exploration of different ideas and solutions among developers and contributors. Privacy concerns and the need for separate API or plugin for reputation systems are also mentioned.</summary>
